iFirst, let's discuss computer booting.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iWhen you press the power button, components like the CPU and memory		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ireceive power and begin executing a pre-installed program on the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
imotherboard called BIOS. BIOS then starts your operating system in the		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ifollowing ways:		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i1. It searches devices in the boot order sequence (optical drive, hard		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   disk, network, etc.) as configured. If a bootable device is found,		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   it executes the code on that device to start the system.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i2. If you press the boot menu key (usually Esc or F12) to manually		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   select the hardware, BIOS executes the code on that hardware.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i3. If BIOS supports UEFI boot and has UEFI settings configured, it		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   automatically invokes the UEFI bootloader saved with the settings		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   or the specified UEFI boot file. This method is more advanced and		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   won't be discussed here. However, if your computer came		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   pre-installed with Windows 8 or is a Mac, you're likely booting via		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
i   UEFI.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iIn the first two methods, BIOS reads the device's MBR (a program code		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
istored on the device, unrelated to partitions like C:, D:, E:). If no		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iMBR exists, it searches for an active partition (marked as "active")		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
ior the only available partition, then boots from the PBR (partition		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
iboot record, invisible in File Explorer). If unsuccessful, BIOS		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
idisplays a "no operating system" error.		{{server_addr}}	{{server_port}}
